[[File:Staatsbegräbnis.jpg|thumb|260px|[[Law enforcement in Austria|Austrian police]] in [[Vienna]].]] '''Crime in Austria''' is combated by a range of [[Law enforcement in Austria|Austrian law enforcement agencies]].
== Crime by type == === Murder === {{Further|List of countries by intentional homicide rate}}
In 2016, Austria (with a population of about 8.74 million) had an intentional homicide rate of 0.53 per 100,000 population - one of the lowest rates in the world. There were a total of 46 intentional homicides in Austria in 2016.<ref name=''Federal Ministry of the Interior - Federal Criminal Police Office''>[http://bundeskriminalamt.at/501/files/BroschuereSicherheit_2016.pdf ''Polizeiliche Kriminalstatistik 2016'', Federal Ministry of the Interior - Federal Criminal Police Office, 26 June 2017.]</ref>
=== Theft === [[File:Österreichische Bundespolizei 09.jpg|thumb|Austrian police at a traffic stop.]] Pickpockets and purse snatchers can be found in the highly populated areas, including areas frequented by tourists, bus and train stations, and on subways.<ref>[https://www.osac.gov/Pages/ContentReportDetails.aspx?cid=12180 "Austria 2012 Crime and Safety Report", United States Department of State, Overseas Security Advisory Council, 13 March 2012.]</ref> Residential burglaries are a significant concern, especially in the more affluent areas.<ref>[https://www.osac.gov/Pages/ContentReportDetails.aspx?cid=12180 "Austria 2012 Crime and Safety Report", United States Department of State, Overseas Security Advisory Council, 13 March 2012.]</ref> The US government rates Vienna as being "medium" for levels of residential crime.<ref>[https://www.osac.gov/Pages/ContentReportDetails.aspx?cid=12180 "Austria 2012 Crime and Safety Report", United States Department of State, Overseas Security Advisory Council, 13 March 2012.]</ref>
In 2004 Austria had the lowest rates of car theft in the EU.<ref>[http://www.europeansafetyobservatory.eu/downloads/EUICS%20-%20The%20Burden%20of%20Crime%20in%20the%20EU.pdf "The Burden of Crime in the EU, A Comparative Analysis of the European Survey of Crime and Safety (EU ICS) 2005", Gallup Europe, 2006.]</ref>
=== Corruption === {{Main|Corruption in Austria}}
Austria has a well-developed institutional and legal system, and most [[corruption]] cases under investigation by a parliamentary committee end with judicial trials and effective judgments. Several significant Austrian corruption cases took place during the 2000s involving land and regional officials, high-level public officials, the central government and, in one instance, the former [[Chancellor]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Austria Corruption Profile-Political Climate|url=http://www.business-anti-corruption.com/country-profiles/europe-central-asia/austria/show-all.aspx|publisher=Business Anti-Corruption Portal|accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref>
In most cases, corrupt practices were related to conflicts of interest, abuse of office, money laundering and influence peddling. The corruption scandals have put into doubt the ethical standards of the political elite.<ref>{{cite web|title=Austria Corruption Profile-Political Climate|url=http://www.business-anti-corruption.com/country-profiles/europe-central-asia/austria/show-all.aspx|publisher=Business Anti-Corruption Portal|accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref> This doubt is reflected in the findings of [[Eurobarometer]] 2012, where two-thirds of respondents perceive national politicians to be corrupt and also the most corrupt institution in Austria.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eurobarometer 2012- Austria|url=http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_374_en.pdf|publisher=The European Commission|accessdate=17 December 2013}}</ref>
== Crime dynamics == Austria is targeted by foreign criminals, with 64 percent of drug-related offences being carried out by criminals who are born abroad.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tirone |last=Jonathan |title=Austria to Tighten Immigration as Crime Increases |publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek |date=19 July 2005}}</ref> According to British criminal Colin Blaney in his autobiography ''Undesirables'', British thieves and confidence tricksters have targeted Austria on account of the fact that it is viewed as a soft touch due to its relatively low crime rates.<ref>{{cite book |first=Colin |last=Blaney |title=Undesirables |year=2014 |publisher=John Blake |isbn=978-1782198970 |pages=130}}</ref>
== By location == Most criminal activity is focused in the larger metropolitan areas.<ref>[https://www.osac.gov/Pages/ContentReportDetails.aspx?cid=12180 "Austria 2012 Crime and Safety Report", United States Department of State, Overseas Security Advisory Council, 13 March 2012.]</ref>
