{{Politics of Guinea-Bissau}}
The '''Guinean League for Ecological Protection''' ({{lang-pt|Liga Guineense para a Protecção Ecológica}}, LIPE) is a [[political party]] in [[Guinea-Bissau]].
==History== The party was established on 20 July 1991 by [[Bubácar Rachid Djaló]], and was legalised on 8 September 1993.<ref name=HD>Peter Karibe Mendy (2013) ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Guinea-Bissau'', Scarecrow Press, p255</ref> In 1994 it joined the [[Union for Change]], an alliance formed to contest the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 1994|1994 general elections]]. Djaló was the Union's presidential candidate, but received only 3% of the vote. However, the UM did win six seats in the [[National People's Assembly (Guinea-Bissau)|National People's Assembly]].
The [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 1999–2000|1999–2000 elections]] saw the UM lose three seats. Djaló remained the alliance's presidential candidate, but again received only 3% of the vote. Following the Union's support for the victorious [[Kumba Ialá]] in the run-off election, Djaló became Secretary of State for Commerce.<ref name=M1>Mendy, p256</ref>
In 2002 LIPE left the UM and joined the [[Electoral Union]] (UE) alliance, which won two seats in the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2004|2004 parliamentary elections]].<ref name=M1/> The UE was dissolved prior to the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2008|2008 parliamentary elections]] and LIPE ran alone, receiving just 233 votes (0.05%). The party's application to contest the [[Guinea-Bissau general election, 2014|2014 general elections]] was rejected by the Supreme Court.<ref>[http://www.anacao.cv/online/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4420:guine-bissau-supremo-chumba-oito-candidaturas-presidenciais-e-sete-partidos&catid=87:destaque&Itemid=475 GUINÉ-BISSAU: SUPREMO “CHUMBA” OITO CANDIDATURAS PRESIDENCIAIS E SETE PARTIDOS] A Nação, 16 March 2014</ref>
